data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_06fff42d37c2c2fa0069cc4bd1ea188194a4d5e01927d422b4","logprobs":[],"output_index":5,"sequence_number":274,"text":"A strong pick under $300 is the SkyView 2‑Person Tent (about $200). It’s roomy for two, easy to set up, and well equipped for 3‑season camping【7:1†source】.\n\nWhat it includes\n- Capacity and seasonality: 2‑person, 3‑season【7:1†source】  \n- Weather protection: Durable, waterproof materials; full rainfly included; double‑stitched seams【7:1†source】  \n- Layout: 2 doors and 2 vestibules (about 8 sq ft each) for gear storage【7:1†source】  \n- Structure: Freestanding design with lightweight aluminum poles【7:1†source】  \n- Ventilation and storage: Mesh panels for airflow; multiple interior pockets【7:1†source】  \n- Visibility: Reflective guy lines and stake points【7:1†source】  \n- Packed weight: ~8 lb (better for car camping or short hikes than ultralight trips)【7:1†source】  \n- Warranty: 1‑year limited warranty【7:4†source】\n\nUser feedback highlights spaciousness, solid weather protection, and straightforward setup, with a few noting the zippers can feel flimsy【7:2†source】【7:0†source】.\n\nIf you’ll backpack frequently and want something lighter than ~8 lb, consider a lighter 2‑person model; otherwise, this offers strong value under $300 with a full feature set【7:1†source】."}

